This is a good and easy course and prof really did a good job on not exposing too much material to the students with very limited math maturity&hellip;
It reviews a lot on the material studied in first/second year calculus. The new material is roughly \(\subseteq \textbf{PMATH 333} \cup \textbf{PMATH 351} \), and some dynamic system, and possibly some computational math.
The prof used ROUNDUP in final mark calculation: \(91.1\to 92 \). Wish it could be applied to other courses&hellip;

This midterm was brutal&hellip; avg was about 65&hellip; and last term was about 78, and added 3 marks for everyone&hellip;
The material (reduction, algorithms, complexity theory) is pretty standard and straightforward if you have a good prof like in Fall 2019.
The notes above is generated from Spring 2021 offering.

Taught by Penny, Cambridge PhD.
Content is hard, assignments are hard, while tests are ok. But if you can&rsquo;t get the test questions after the first look, you won&rsquo;t have time to finish them&hellip;
She will be teaching 442 next term (Fall 2019).

This course is taught by a single instructor all over the terms. Some said it&rsquo;s easy to get 98&hellip; I am not sure why she gave me such a low mark&hellip;
Anyway, just prepare the slides and textbooks before the final&hellip;
Here is my presentation.
Also, we were required to submit a book review. I chose China in Ten Words by Yu Hua. Here is the reflection.

Taught by Robert Garbary. Also hold an online session at the same time, and hold a Skype office hours for them&hellip;
His notes was summarized, so no need to copy tons of examples.
He also made a joke with his mic. He went outside to drink some water. When he was still outside the classroom, he said, with his mic on:&ldquo;I know you can hear me.&rdquo;
Remarks 235 is more well-structured than 136&hellip; If you screwed up with 136, 235 is still ok.
Notes I started to learn LaTeX from this term&hellip; So here is a set of compact notes.

Taught by Spiro. You can tell he is knowledgeable and ways he talks.
He coordinated math 237 for this term (and last term). The biggest change is that he no longer used the official coursenote, which is full of errors and bad proofs. Instead, he used Vector Calculus. Also, during these two terms, 12 assignments are required to be submitted, even during midterm week&hellip; Assignments did give a taste of how exams look like, so exams are full of calculations with little proofs.
His research interests are Geometry &amp; Topology (maybe more), then he taught pmath 365 during next available term (1191). However, it seems that the lecture was not easy to follow&hellip;
Many math 148 students don&rsquo;t like this course since drawing \(z=x^2+y^2\) is boring&hellip; They would rather do proofs&hellip;
